[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] In mathematics, especially in order theory, the **greatest element** of a subset S of a partially ordered set (poset) is an element of S that is greater than every other element of S .
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] By switching the side of the relation that s is on in the above definition, the definition of a least element of S is obtained.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] If $(P,\leq )$ is also a partially ordered set then S can have at most one greatest element and it can have at most one least element.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] Whenever a greatest element of S exists and is unique then this element is called ***the* greatest element of S**.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] The terminology ***the* least element of S** is defined similarly.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] If $(P,\leq )$ has a greatest element (resp. a least element) then this element is also called *a **top*** (resp.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] Greatest elements are closely related to upper bounds.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] Thus g is a greatest element of S if and only if g is an upper bound of S *in S*.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] If u is an upper bound of S *in P* that is not an upper bound of S *in S* (which can happen if and only if $u\not \in S$ ) then u can *not* be a greatest element of S (however, it may be possible that some other element *is* a greatest element of S ).
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] In particular, it is possible for S to simultaneously *not* have a greatest element *and* for there to exist some upper bound of S *in P*.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] Even if a set has some upper bounds, it need not have a greatest element, as shown by the example of the negative real numbers.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] This example also demonstrates that the existence of a least upper bound (the number 0 in this case) does not imply the existence of a greatest element either.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] A greatest element of a subset of a preordered set should not be confused with a maximal element of the set, which are elements that are not strictly smaller than any other element in the set.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] A set can have several maximal elements without having a greatest element.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] Like upper bounds and maximal elements, greatest elements may fail to exist.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] In a totally ordered set the maximal element and the greatest element coincide; and it is also called **maximum**; in the case of function values it is also called the **absolute maximum**, to avoid confusion with a local maximum.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] The dual terms are **minimum** and **absolute minimum**.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] Together they are called the **absolute extrema**.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] Similar conclusions hold for least elements.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] One of the most important differences between a greatest element g and a maximal element m of a preordered set $(P,\leq )$ has to do with what elements they are comparable to.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] Two elements $x,y\in P$ are said to be *comparable* if $x\leq y$ or $y\leq x$ ; they are called *incomparable* if they are not comparable.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] Because preorders are reflexive (which means that $x\leq x$ is true for all elements x ), every element x is always comparable to itself.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] Consequently, the only pairs of elements that could possibly be incomparable are *distinct* pairs.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] In general, however, preordered sets (and even directed partially ordered sets) may have elements that are incomparable.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] By definition, an element $g\in P$ is a greatest element of $(P,\leq )$ if $s\leq g,$ for every $s\in P$ ; so by its very definition, a greatest element of $(P,\leq )$ must, in particular, be comparable to *every* element in $P.$ This is not required of maximal elements.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] Maximal elements of $(P,\leq )$ are *not* required to be comparable to every element in $P.$ This is because unlike the definition of "greatest element", the definition of "maximal element" includes an important *if* statement.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] Consequently, $(S,\leq )$ can not possibly have a greatest element (because a greatest element of S would, in particular, have to be comparable to *every* element of S but S has no such element).
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] However, *every* element $m\in S$ is a maximal element of $(S,\leq )$ because there is exactly one element in S that is both comparable to m and $\geq m,$ that element being m itself (which of course, is $\leq m$ ).
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] For example, suppose that R is a non-empty set and define a preorder $\,\leq \,$ on R by declaring that $i\leq j$ *always* holds for all $i,j\in R.$ The directed preordered set $(R,\leq )$ is partially ordered if and only if R has exactly one element.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] All pairs of elements from R are comparable and *every* element of R is a greatest element (and thus also a maximal element) of $(R,\leq ).$ So in particular, if R has at least two elements then $(R,\leq )$ has multiple *distinct* greatest elements.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] The least and greatest element of the whole partially ordered set play a special role and are also called **bottom** (⊥) and **top** (⊤), or **zero** (0) and **unit** (1), respectively.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] If both exist, the poset is called a **bounded poset**.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] The notation of 0 and 1 is used preferably when the poset is a complemented lattice, and when no confusion is likely, i.e. when one is not talking about partial orders of numbers that already contain elements 0 and 1 different from bottom and top.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] The existence of least and greatest elements is a special completeness property of a partial order.
[src:strictness-analysis/bottom-element] Further introductory information is found in the article on order theory.
[src:strictness-analysis/divergence-computer-science] In computer science, a computation is said to **diverge** if it does not terminate or terminates in an exceptional state.
[src:strictness-analysis/divergence-computer-science] In domains where computations are expected to be infinite, such as process calculi, a computation is said to diverge if it fails to be productive (i.e. to continue producing an action within a finite amount of time).
[src:strictness-analysis/divergence-computer-science] Various subfields of computer science use varying, but mathematically precise, definitions of what it means for a computation to converge or diverge.
[src:strictness-analysis/divergence-computer-science] In abstract rewriting, an abstract rewriting system is called convergent if it is both confluent and terminating.
[src:strictness-analysis/divergence-computer-science] The notation *t* ↓ *n* means that *t* reduces to normal form *n* in zero or more reductions, *t*↓ means *t* reduces to some normal form in zero or more reductions, and *t*↑ means *t* does not reduce to a normal form; the latter is impossible in a terminating rewriting system.
[src:strictness-analysis/divergence-computer-science] In the lambda calculus an expression is divergent if it has no normal form.
[src:strictness-analysis/divergence-computer-science] In denotational semantics an object function *f* : *A* → *B* can be modelled as a mathematical function $f:A\cup \{\perp \}\rightarrow B\cup \{\perp \}$ where ⊥ (bottom) indicates that the object function or its argument diverges.
[src:strictness-analysis/divergence-computer-science] In the calculus of communicating sequential processes (CSP), divergence occurs when a process performs an endless series of hidden actions.
[src:strictness-analysis/divergence-computer-science] One semantic model of CSP is the failures-divergences model, which refines the stable failures model by distinguishing processes based on the sets of traces after which they can diverge.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] In a programming language, an **evaluation strategy** is a set of rules for evaluating expressions.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] The notion of reduction strategy is distinct, although some authors conflate the two terms and the definition of each term is not widely agreed upon.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] A programming language's evaluation strategy is part of its high-level semantics.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Some languages, such as PureScript, have variants with different evaluation strategies.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Some declarative languages, such as Datalog, support multiple evaluation strategies.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Just like in mathematics, evaluation is the process of finding the value corresponding to an expression.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] The calling convention consists of the low-level platform-specific details of parameter passing.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] To illustrate, executing a function call `f(a, b)` may first evaluate the arguments `a` and `b`, store the results in references or memory locations `ref_a` and `ref_b`, then evaluate the function's body with those references passed in.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] This gives the function the ability to look up the original argument values passed in through dereferencing the parameters (some languages use specific operators to perform this), to modify them via assignment as if they were local variables, and to return values via the references.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] This is the call-by-reference evaluation strategy.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] This is a table of evaluation strategies and representative languages by year introduced.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] The representative languages are listed in chronological order, starting with the language(s) that introduced the strategy and followed by prominent languages that use the strategy.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] While the order of operations defines the abstract syntax tree of the expression, the evaluation order defines the order in which expressions are evaluated.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] outputs `213` due to OCaml's right-to-left evaluation order.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] The evaluation order is mainly visible in code with side effects, but it also affects the performance of the code because a rigid order inhibits instruction scheduling.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] For this reason language standards such as C++ traditionally left the order unspecified, although languages such as Java and C# define the evaluation order as left-to-right and the C++17 standard has added constraints on the evaluation order.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Common Lisp, Eiffel and Java evaluate function arguments left-to-right.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Scheme requires the execution order to be the sequential execution of an unspecified permutation of the arguments.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] OCaml similarly leaves the order unspecified, but in practice evaluates arguments right-to-left due to the design of its abstract machine.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] A **non-strict evaluation order** is an evaluation order that is not strict, that is, a function may return a result before all of its arguments are fully evaluated.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] The prototypical example is **normal order evaluation**, which does not evaluate any of the arguments until they are needed in the body of the function.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Normal order evaluation has the property that it terminates without error whenever any other evaluation order would have terminated without error.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] The name "normal order" comes from the lambda calculus, where normal order reduction will find a normal form if there is one (it is a "normalizing" reduction strategy).
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is classified in this article as a binding technique rather than an evaluation order.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] But this distinction is not always followed and some authors define lazy evaluation as normal order evaluation or vice-versa, or confuse non-strictness with lazy evaluation.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Conditional expressions similarly use non-strict evaluation - only one of the branches is evaluated.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] With normal order evaluation, expressions containing an expensive computation, an error, or an infinite loop will be ignored if not needed, allowing the specification of user-defined control flow constructs, a facility not available with applicative order evaluation.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Normal order evaluation uses complex structures such as thunks for unevaluated expressions, compared to the call stack used in applicative order evaluation.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Normal order evaluation has historically had a lack of usable debugging tools due to its complexity.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] In call by value (or pass by value), the evaluated value of the argument expression is bound to the corresponding variable in the function (frequently by copying the value into a new memory region).
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] If the function or procedure is able to assign values to its parameters, only its local variable is assigned—that is, anything passed into a function call is unchanged in the caller's scope when the function returns.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Strictly speaking, under call by value, no operations performed by the called routine can be visible to the caller, other than as part of the return value.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] This implies a form of purely functional programming in the implementation semantics.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] However, the circumlocution "call by value where the value is a reference" has become common in some languages, for example, the Java community.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Compared to traditional pass by value, the value which is passed is not a value as understood by the ordinary meaning of value, such as an integer that can be written as a literal, but an implementation-internal reference handle.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Mutations to this reference handle are visible in the caller.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Due to the visible mutation, this form of "call by value" is more properly referred to as call by sharing.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] In purely functional languages, values and data structures are immutable, so there is no possibility for a function to modify any of its arguments.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] As such, there is typically no semantic difference between passing by value and passing by reference or a pointer to the data structure, and implementations frequently use call by reference internally for the efficiency benefits.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Nonetheless, these languages are typically described as call by value languages.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Call by reference (or pass by reference) is an evaluation strategy where a parameter is bound to an implicit reference to the variable used as argument, rather than a copy of its value.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] This typically means that the function can modify (i.e., assign to) the variable used as argument—something that will be seen by its caller.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Call by reference can therefore be used to provide an additional channel of communication between the called function and the calling function.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Pass by reference can significantly improve performance: calling a function with a many-megabyte structure as an argument does not have to copy the large structure, only the reference to the structure (which is generally a machine word and only a few bytes).
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] However, a call-by-reference language makes it more difficult for a programmer to track the effects of a function call, and may introduce subtle bugs.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Due to variation in syntax, the difference between call by reference (where the reference type is implicit) and call by sharing (where the reference type is explicit) is often unclear on first glance.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] A simple litmus test is if it's possible to write a traditional `swap(a, b)` function in the language.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Therefore, Fortran's `inout` intent implements call-by-reference; any variable can be implicitly converted to a reference handle.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] where an explicit `Box` type must be used to introduce a handle.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Java is call-by-sharing but not call-by-reference.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Call by copy-restore—also known as "copy-in copy-out", "call by value result", "call by value return" (as termed in the Fortran community)—is a variation of call by reference.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] With call by copy-restore, the contents of the argument are copied to a new variable local to the call invocation.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] The function may then modify this variable, similarly to call by reference, but as the variable is local, the modifications are not visible outside of the call invocation during the call.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] When the function call returns, the updated contents of this variable are copied back to overwrite the original argument ("restored").
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] The semantics of call by copy-restore is similar in many cases to call by reference, but differs when two or more function arguments alias one another (i.e., point to the same variable in the caller's environment).
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Under call by reference, writing to one argument will affect the other during the function's execution.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Under call by copy-restore, writing to one argument will not affect the other during the function's execution, but at the end of the call, the values of the two arguments may differ, and it is unclear which argument is copied back first and therefore what value the caller's variable receives.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] For example, Ada specifies that the copy-out assignment for each `in out` or `out` parameter occurs in an arbitrary order.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] If the program returned 1 it would be copying right-to-left, and under call by reference semantics the program would return 3.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] When the reference is passed to the caller uninitialized (for example an `out` parameter in Ada as opposed to an `in out` parameter), this evaluation strategy may be called "call by result".
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] This strategy has gained attention in multiprocessing and remote procedure calls, as unlike call-by-reference it does not require frequent communication between threads of execution for variable access.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Call by sharing (also known as "pass by sharing", "call by object", or "call by object-sharing") is an evaluation strategy that is intermediate between call by value and call by reference.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Rather than every variable being exposed as a reference, only a specific class of values, termed "references", "boxed types", or "objects", have reference semantics, and it is the addresses of these pointers that are passed into the function.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Like call by value, the value of the address passed is a copy, and direct assignment to the parameter of the function overwrites the copy and is not visible to the calling function.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Like call by reference, mutating the target of the pointer is visible to the calling function.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Mutations of a mutable object within the function are visible to the caller because the object is not copied or cloned—it is *shared*, hence the name "call by sharing".
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] The technique was first noted by Barbara Liskov in 1974 for the CLU language.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] The term "call by sharing" as used in this article is not in common use; the terminology is inconsistent across different sources.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] For example, in the Java community, they say that Java is call by value.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] For immutable objects, there is no real difference between call by sharing and call by value, except if object identity is visible in the language.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] The use of call by sharing with mutable objects is an alternative to input/output parameters: the parameter is not assigned to (the argument is not overwritten and object identity is not changed), but the object (argument) is mutated.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] outputs `[1]` because the `append` method modifies the object on which it is called.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] In contrast, assignments within a function are not noticeable to the caller.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Some authors treat `&` as part of the syntax of calling `swap`.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Under this view, C supports the call-by-reference parameter passing strategy.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Other authors take a differing view that the presented implementation of `swap` in C is only a simulation of call-by-reference using pointers.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Under this "simulation" view, mutable variables in C are not first-class (that is, l-values are not expressions), rather pointer types are.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Because in this program, `swap` operates on pointers and cannot change the pointers themselves, but only the values the pointers point to, this view holds that C's main evaluation strategy is more similar to call-by-sharing.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Semantically, this is equivalent to the C examples.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] As such, many authors consider call-by-address to be a unique parameter passing strategy distinct from call-by-value, call-by-reference, and call-by-sharing.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] In logic programming, the evaluation of an expression may simply correspond to the unification of the terms involved combined with the application of some form of resolution.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Unification must be classified as a strict binding strategy because it is fully performed.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] However, unification can also be performed on unbounded variables, so calls may not necessarily commit to final values for all its variables.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Call by name is an evaluation strategy where the arguments to a function are not evaluated before the function is called—rather, they are substituted directly into the function body (using capture-avoiding substitution) and then left to be evaluated whenever they appear in the function.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] If an argument is not used in the function body, the argument is never evaluated; if it is used several times, it is re-evaluated each time it appears.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Call-by-name evaluation is occasionally preferable to call-by-value evaluation.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] If a function's argument is not used in the function, call by name will save time by not evaluating the argument, whereas call by value will evaluate it regardless.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] If the argument is a non-terminating computation, the advantage is enormous.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] However, when the function argument is used, call by name is often slower, requiring a mechanism such as a thunk.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] .NET languages can simulate call by name using delegates or `Expression<T>` parameters.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] The latter results in an abstract syntax tree being given to the function.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Eiffel provides agents, which represent an operation to be evaluated when needed.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Java programs can accomplish similar lazy evaluation using lambda expressions and the `java.util.function.Supplier<T>` interface.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Call by need is a memoized variant of call by name, where, if the function argument is evaluated, that value is stored for subsequent use.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] If the argument is pure (i.e., free of side effects), this produces the same results as call by name, saving the cost of recomputing the argument.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Haskell is a well-known language that uses call-by-need evaluation.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Because evaluation of expressions may happen arbitrarily far into a computation, Haskell supports only side effects (such as mutation) via the use of monads.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] This eliminates any unexpected behavior from variables whose values change prior to their delayed evaluation.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] In R's implementation of call by need, all arguments are passed, meaning that R allows arbitrary side effects.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is the most common implementation of call-by-need semantics, but variations like optimistic evaluation exist. .NET languages implement call by need using the type `Lazy<T>`.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Graph reduction is an efficient implementation of lazy evaluation.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Call by macro expansion is similar to call by name, but uses textual substitution rather than capture-avoiding substitution.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Macro substitution may therefore result in variable capture, leading to mistakes and undesired behavior.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Hygienic macros avoid this problem by checking for and replacing shadowed variables that are not parameters.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] "Call by future", also known as "parallel call by name" or "lenient evaluation", is a concurrent evaluation strategy combining non-strict semantics with eager evaluation.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] The method requires fine-grained dynamic scheduling and synchronization but is suitable for massively parallel machines.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] The strategy creates a future (promise) for the function's body and each of its arguments.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] These futures are computed concurrently with the flow of the rest of the program.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] When a future A requires the value of another future B that has not yet been computed, future A blocks until future B finishes computing and has a value.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] If future B has already finished computing the value is returned immediately.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Conditionals block until their condition is evaluated, and lambdas do not create futures until they are fully applied.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] If implemented with processes or threads, creating a future will spawn one or more new processes or threads (for the promises), accessing the value will synchronize these with the main thread, and terminating the computation of the future corresponds to killing the promises computing its value.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] If implemented with a coroutine, as in .NET async/await, creating a future calls a coroutine (an async function), which may yield to the caller, and in turn be yielded back to when the value is used, cooperatively multitasking.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] The strategy is non-deterministic, as the evaluation can occur at any time between creation of the future (i.e., when the expression is given) and use of the future's value.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] The strategy is non-strict because the function body may return a value before the arguments are evaluated.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] However, in most implementations, execution may still get stuck evaluating an unneeded argument.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] may either have `g` finish before `f`, and output 1, or may result in an error due to evaluating `1/0`.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Call-by-future is similar to call by need in that values are computed only once.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] With careful handling of errors and nontermination, in particular terminating futures partway through if it is determined they will not be needed, call-by-future also has the same termination properties as call-by-need evaluation.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] However, call-by-future may perform unnecessary speculative work compared to call-by-need, such as deeply evaluating a lazy data structure.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] This can be avoided by using lazy futures that do not start computation until it is certain the value is needed.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] Optimistic evaluation is a call-by-need variant where the function's argument is partly evaluated in a call-by-value style for some amount of time (which may be adjusted at runtime).
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] After that time has passed, evaluation is aborted and the function is applied using call by need.
[src:strictness-analysis/eager-evaluation] This approach avoids some of call-by-need's runtime expenses while retaining desired termination characteristics.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-function] In computer science and computer programming, a function f is said to be **strict** if, when applied to a non-terminating expression, it also fails to terminate.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-function] A **strict function** in the denotational semantics of programming languages is a function *f* where $f\left(\perp \right)=\perp$ .
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-function] The entity $\perp$ , called *bottom*, denotes an expression that does not return a normal value, either because it loops endlessly or because it aborts due to an error such as division by zero.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-function] A function that is not strict is called **non-strict**.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-function] A strict programming language is one in which user-defined functions are always strict.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-function] Intuitively, non-strict functions correspond to control structures.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-function] Operationally, a strict function is one that always evaluates its argument; a non-strict function is one that might not evaluate some of its arguments.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-function] Functions having more than one parameter can be strict or non-strict in each parameter independently, as well as *jointly strict* in several parameters simultaneously.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-function] As an example, the `if-then-else` expression of many programming languages, called `?:` in languages inspired by C, may be thought of as a function of three parameters.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-function] However, it is jointly strict in its second and third parameters, since `if(true, $\perp$ , $\perp$ ) = $\perp$` and `if(false, $\perp$ , $\perp$ ) = $\perp$`.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-function] In a non-strict functional programming language, strictness analysis refers to any algorithm used to prove the strictness of a function with respect to one or more of its arguments.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-function] Such functions can be compiled to a more efficient calling convention, such as call by value, without changing the meaning of the enclosing program.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-programming-language] A **strict programming language** is a programming language that only allows strict functions (functions whose parameters must be evaluated completely before they may be called) to be defined by the user.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-programming-language] A **non-strict programming language** allows the user to define non-strict functions, and hence may allow lazy evaluation.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-programming-language] In most non-strict languages, the non-strictness extends to data constructors.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-programming-language] A strict programming language is a programming language which employs a strict programming paradigm, allowing only strict functions (functions whose parameters must be evaluated completely before they may be called) to be defined by the user.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-programming-language] A non-strict programming language allows the user to define non-strict functions, and hence may allow lazy evaluation.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-programming-language] Strict programming languages are often associated with eager evaluation, and non-strict languages with lazy evaluation, but other evaluation strategies are possible in each case.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-programming-language] The terms "eager programming language" and "lazy programming language" are often used as synonyms for "strict programming language" and "non-strict programming language" respectively.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-programming-language] Nearly all programming languages in common use today are strict.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-programming-language] Examples include C#, Java, Perl (all versions, i.e., through versions 5 and 7), Python, Ruby, Common Lisp, and ML.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-programming-language] Some strict programming languages include features that mimic laziness.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-programming-language] Raku (formerly named Perl 6) has lazy lists, Python has generating functions, and Julia provides a macro system to build non-strict functions, as does Scheme.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-programming-language] Examples for non-strict languages are Haskell, R, Miranda, and Clean.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-programming-language] This allows conceptually infinite data structures (such as the list of all prime numbers) to be manipulated in the same way as ordinary finite data structures.
[src:strictness-analysis/strict-programming-language] It also allows for the use of very large but finite data structures such as the complete game tree of chess.
[src:strictness-analysis/total-functional-programming] Every function must be a total (as opposed to partial) function.
[src:strictness-analysis/total-functional-programming] That is, it must have a definition for everything inside its domain.
[src:strictness-analysis/total-functional-programming] These restrictions mean that total functional programming is not Turing-complete.
[src:strictness-analysis/total-functional-programming] However, the set of algorithms that can be used is still huge.
[src:strictness-analysis/total-functional-programming] For example, any algorithm for which an asymptotic upper bound can be calculated (by a program that itself only uses Walther recursion) can be trivially transformed into a provably-terminating function by using the upper bound as an extra argument decremented on each iteration or recursion.
[src:strictness-analysis/total-functional-programming] For example, quicksort is not trivially shown to be substructural recursive, but it only recurs to a maximum depth of the length of the vector (worst-case time complexity O(*n*2)).
[src:strictness-analysis/total-functional-programming] Some classes of algorithms have no theoretical upper bound but do have a practical upper bound (for example, some heuristic-based algorithms can be programmed to "give up" after so many recursions, also ensuring termination).
[src:strictness-analysis/total-functional-programming] Another outcome of total functional programming is that both strict evaluation and lazy evaluation result in the same behaviour, in principle; however, one or the other may still be preferable (or even required) for performance reasons.
[src:strictness-analysis/total-functional-programming] In total functional programming, a distinction is made between data and codata—the former is finitary, while the latter is potentially infinite.
[src:strictness-analysis/total-functional-programming] Such potentially infinite data structures are used for applications such as I/O.
[src:strictness-analysis/total-functional-programming] Using codata entails the usage of such operations as corecursion.
[src:strictness-analysis/total-functional-programming] However, it is possible to do I/O in a total functional programming language (with dependent types) also without codata.
[src:strictness-analysis/total-functional-programming] Both Epigram and Charity could be considered total functional programming languages, even though they do not work in the way Turner specifies in his paper.
[src:strictness-analysis/total-functional-programming] So could programming directly in plain System F, in Martin-Löf type theory or the Calculus of Constructions.
